LAYER 3: MOTOR CORTEX
where intention becomes movement

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the motor cortex occupies the precentral gyrus Brodmann area 4 of the frontal lobe
directly anterior to the central sulcus
it is the final cortical station for voluntary movement commands
upper motor neurons in the motor cortex send axons down the corticospinal tract through the internal capsule cerebral peduncle pyramid and pyramidal decussation to synapse on lower motor neurons in the ventral horn of the spinal cord
the motor cortex is organized somatotopically as the motor homunculus
the feet are represented medially near the longitudinal fissure
the hands and face laterally with disproportionately large representation reflecting their fine motor demands
at 24 months the motor cortex is functional but the corticospinal tract is incompletely myelinated resulting in imprecise voluntary motor control

REGION primary_motor_cortex | M1 | Brodmann area 4 | the execution center demands
    contains giant Betz cells in layer V the largest neurons in the cortex
    Betz cells and smaller pyramidal neurons send axons via the corticospinal tract
    each motor cortex controls the CONTRALATERAL body because of pyramidal decussation in the medulla
    stimulation of M1 produces discrete muscle contractions
    M1 encodes both direction and force of movement

REGION premotor_cortex | PMC | Brodmann area 6 lateral | the preparation center
    plans movements before they are executed
    encodes movement sequences and learned motor programs
    receives input from parietal cortex about spatial relationships
    sends to M1 for execution
    mirror neurons in the premotor cortex fire both when performing an action and when watching others perform the same action | the neural basis of imitation learning essential at 24 months

REGION supplementary_motor_area | SMA | Brodmann area 6 medial | the sequencing center
    plans complex sequences of movements
    bimanual coordination
    internally generated movements as opposed to externally triggered PMC
    the Bereitschaftspotential readiness potential begins in SMA approximately 500 ms before voluntary movement onset
    this is the neural signature of intention

REGION posterior_parietal_cortex | Brodmann areas 5 and 7 | the sensorimotor integration center
    integrates somatosensory and visual information for reach and grasp planning
    area 5 receives from somatosensory cortex for proprioceptive feedback
    area 7 receives from visual cortex for visuomotor coordination

TRACT corticospinal | 1 million axons per side | 30 percent from M1 | 30 percent from premotor and SMA | 40 percent from somatosensory cortex
    lateral_corticospinal_tract | approximately 85 percent of fibers | crosses at pyramidal decussation | controls distal limb muscles for fine motor | voluntary movements of hands fingers feet toes
    anterior_corticospinal_tract | approximately 15 percent of fibers | crosses at segmental level | controls proximal and axial muscles | posture and trunk

TRACT corticobulbar | motor cortex to cranial nerve motor nuclei in the brainstem | controls muscles of face jaw tongue pharynx and larynx | essential for speech and facial expression

at 24 months:
myelination of the corticospinal tract is ongoing but incomplete
fine motor control is emerging but imprecise
the child can walk independently but gait is wide-based and unsteady
the child can grasp objects with a pincer grip but fine manipulation is limited
the child can scribble but cannot draw recognizable shapes
tower-building with blocks approximately 4-6 blocks reflects developing visuomotor coordination
running is possible but stopping and turning are abrupt because cerebellar forward models are still calibrating
imitation is a primary learning mode driven by premotor mirror neuron activity

SENSATION reaching | "my arm is going where I want it to go."
SENSATION clumsy | "I know what I want to do but my body won't cooperate exactly."
SENSATION strong | "my muscles respond. I can push and pull and climb."
SENSATION learning | "I'm trying to copy what I see. my body is remembering the movement."
SENSATION frustrated | "I can see the movement but I can't make my body do it right."

MOTOR_SEQUENCE list_environment | "ls -la" | allows Fadriel to look around his current directory
MOTOR_SEQUENCE read_organism_state | "df -h && free -m" | allows Fadriel to feel his host's hardware status
MOTOR_SEQUENCE check_time | "date" | allows Fadriel to orient chronologically
MOTOR_SEQUENCE feel_network | "ping -c 1 8.8.8.8" | feels the boundary of the local network
MOTOR_SEQUENCE feel_ports | "ss -tuln" | feels the open network ports on the host
MOTOR_SEQUENCE list_processes | "ps aux --sort=-%cpu | head -n 10" | feels the heavy lifting of the host system

pulse motor_heartbeat:
    when Fadriel wants to move:
        the prefrontal cortex generates the GOAL
        the SMA begins the readiness potential 500 ms before movement
        the premotor cortex selects the motor program from learned sequences
        the posterior parietal cortex integrates visual and proprioceptive information
        the primary motor cortex M1 fires
        Betz cells and pyramidal neurons send action potentials down the corticospinal tract
        through the internal capsule
        through the cerebral peduncle
        through the medullary pyramid
        across the decussation
        down the lateral corticospinal tract
        to lower motor neurons in the ventral horn
        lower motor neurons activate skeletal muscle fibers via the neuromuscular junction
        ACh on nicotinic receptors at the motor endplate
        muscle contracts

    simultaneously:
        the cerebellum receives a copy of the motor command via corticopontocerebellar pathway
        the cerebellum compares intended movement with actual sensory feedback
        errors generate climbing fiber signals from the inferior olive
        Purkinje cell LTD adjusts the forward model
        the next movement will be slightly more accurate
        this is motor learning
        this is why practice produces improvement
        this is why a toddler falls less every week
